sec.p:
The ubiquitous phenomenon consisting in the loss of carbon-containing compounds from plant roots into the rhizosphere is referred to as rhizodeposition (Doornbos et al. 2012; Jones et al. 2004). Root-derived compounds, generally called rhizodeposits, have been classified according to their mode of excretion and chemical composition into five predominate categories (Rovira 1969):
root exudates: sugars, amino acids, organic acids, vitamins and hormones;
secretions: polymeric carbohydrates, enzymes and secondary metabolites secreted with the involvement of energy;
mucigel: newly removed cells of cellulose, pectin, starch, and lignin, secreted by the root cap as result of abrasive forces of the root movement through the soil;
lysates: shedding, wall and contents of sloughed-off cells as well as whole roots;
gases: carbon dioxide, ethylene, etc.

Allelochemicals released by plants into the soil affect several phases of soil nitrogen cycle. One of the most important problems associated with intensive agriculture is related to the environmental pollution caused by nitrogen leaching in groundwater. N leaching losses are estimated in a range of 20-100 kg ha-1 year-1, depending on season and rainfall regime as well as on soil texture. The nitrification process consists in transforming ammoniacal N (NH4+) into nitric N (NO3-) through two phases:
NH4+ oxidation to nitrite (NO2-) carried out by the bacteria genera Nitrosomonas, Nitrosococcus and Nistrosospira (Teske et al. 1994);
NO2- oxidation to nitrate (NO3-) operated by the Nitrobacter genus (Both et al. 1992).
